    {
      "overview_item_type": "essential_ideas",
      "overview_item_content_type": "html",
      "overview_item_title": "Essential Ideas",
      "overview_item_data": {
        "overview_item_data_type": "list",
        "overview_item_data_items": [
          "The formula for calculating the area of a circle is <math><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>, where <math><mi>A</mi></math> is the area, <math><mi>r</mi></math> is the length of the radius of the circle, and <math><mi>π</mi></math> is sometimes represented using an approximation, such as 3.14.",
          "When solving problems involving circles, use the circumference formula to determine the distance around a circle and the area formula to determine the space inside a circle.",
          "When you double the length of a circle's radius, you quadruple its area. The area is quadrupled rather than doubled because in a circle's area formula, <math><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>, the length of the radius is squared."
        ]
      }
    },
